Scientists have found an animal that can live for 500 years
An international team of biologists has concluded that the longest-living vertebrate is the Greenland polar shark, which can live for about 500 years, RT reports.
Scientists conducted radiocarbon analysis of the eye lenses of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, which is more than five metres long, can be between 272 and 512 years old.
Biologists believe that a low metabolism plays an important role in shark longevity, leading to slow development.
Female Greenland sharks do not reach sexual maturity until they are 150 years old.
Previously, it was thought that the longest-living vertebrate animal was the shark's "neighbor," the bowhead whale.
The oldest specimen known to scientists was just over 210 years old.
