Is it worth going to a health resort if there are no health problems?
Our expert is Olga Bogush, Chief Medical Officer of the sanatorium.
And if a person is healthy, just tired of work, should they go to a health resort?
Health resort rest is necessary for us not only for the treatment, but also for the prevention of diseases.
In a health resort, a person can check the condition of his or her body and receive recommendations from a doctor on how to live, so that his or her health does not deteriorate.
Such recommendations will not be superfluous to anyone.
"Just tired of work" is an important signal from the body, and should not be dismissed.
Constant stress and mental and physical exhaustion can lead to depression and chronic fatigue syndrome.
And about 90% of visitors experience stress.
Moreover, people from large cities between the ages of 45 and 55 are the most exposed to it.
So it is better not to complicate the situation and let yourself rest in time.
Research shows that 98% of people reduce their biological age during their stay at a health resort.
Modern health resorts offer a comfortable vacation for the whole family.
So if you want to spend your holidays with your children, you don't have to part with them.
For children, even the youngest ones, there are health programs that include diagnostic services, pediatrician consultations, tests, and therapeutic services.
For example, swimming (many health resorts have children's pools), inhalations, a special diet, massages, oxygen cocktails, and therapeutic exercise.
The course of procedures is determined by a doctor taking into account individual indications and the characteristics of the growing organism.
In addition, there is, as a rule, a children's club with animators, where children can attend play classes and various workshops.
Some health resorts even open their doors to guests with babies, provide the necessary facilities for infants, and provide the services of an experienced nanny.
Mild winters, long summers, and an abundance of sunny days per year (more than 300) create good conditions for year-round recreation at the resorts of the Caucasus Mineral Waters.
And then the body needs rest not only in the summer.
So do not be afraid of the weather outside the window, especially as most procedures are conducted indoors and do not depend on the season.
In general, it is advisable to conduct spa treatment twice a year, especially for people of mature age.
The main feature of the Caucasus Mineral Waters region is, of course, the medicinal mineral springs: Slavyanovsky, Smirnovsky, Yessentuki, Narzan.
Their waters have unique properties and affect different body systems.
Water differs in temperature, salt quantity, total mineralization, chemical and gas composition.
The doctor selects the water depending on the patient's well-being.
Thus, Narzan has an anti-inflammatory, immunomodulatory effect, restores the functions of the gastrointestinal tract and metabolism.
"Yessentuki-4" affects the gastrointestinal tract and lowers sugar levels.
"New Yessentuki" has anti-inflammatory, choleretic and diuretic effects.
Slavyanovskaya water has the same effects.
When prescribing water, the doctor must take into account the state of the cardiovascular system.
If there are signs of hypertension, it selects less salty water because salts trap fluid, leading to increased pressure.
Intake of mineral water requires adherence to a regime: the water should be drunk at a certain time, in the right amount and at a specific temperature.
Now various cosmetic procedures for the face and body are also available in health resorts.
What kinds of health improvement based on the natural features of the North Caucasus can be obtained at resorts in this region?
Near Pyatigorsk, for example, there is the salt lake Tambukan, mud from which is useful for joints, spine, and internal organs.
It has an anti-inflammatory, absorbing, immunomodulatory effect.
These are health walks along individually designed routes.
They are especially popular in Kislovodsk, where there is a huge Resort Park (the second largest in Europe).
They are popular in Kislovodsk, which is located in close proximity to the Narzan mineral spring.
There you can also take baths of wine, pearl, iodine-bromine, selenium, sage-liquorice, depending on what your doctor prescribes.
Let's prolong the fruit-bearing period.
What can be done to keep the harvest going until the end of the season?
Yuliya Belopukhova, an agronomist and dacha dweller, tells us.
It is time for the tall tomatoes to get a haircut: remove the new stepsons, cut off the top of their heads, remove all the leaves up to the penultimate brush with the fruit and the flowerbeds with small ties - they will not have time to ripen.
We feed all tomatoes, regardless of the "constitution," as well as peppers and eggplant, with ash-superphosphate extract, and treat them with bio-preparations (Dovriatel - to accelerate the filling and growth of the fruit, Fitosporin-M, Fitolavin, Gamair, Baktofit - against diseases, Immunocytofit - to enhance immunity, Bitoxybacillin, Lepidocide, Fitoverm - if there are pests).
Of the chemicals, only copper sulphur, colloidal sulphur, and green soap should be used at the end of summer.
We do the last watering of the plants.
In the greenhouse, lower the long-plaited cucumbers so that the lower, bare part of the stem (25-40 cm) lies on the ground, water it with warm water and Zircon solution, and cover the stem with 5-7 cm of compost.
Extending the fruiting of courgette is also easy: cut off the old leaves, pour warm water and a solution of complex fertilizer, pour fertile soil under the bush.
To protect against night-time cold, place an arc with cover material over the bed.
Keep the plants open during the day, and close them after sunset.
Signs of the end.
What indicates that Russia is emerging from the crisis?
Economists have seen signs that Russia is emerging from the longest recession in two decades.
According to analysts polled by Bloomberg, Russia's GDP is showing positive dynamics - in the second quarter, GDP fell by 0.8% year on year.
This figure is the lowest since the beginning of 2015.
According to the latest Rosstat data, the Russian economy slowed to 0.6% in the second quarter.
The Central Bank and the Ministry of Economic Development have also recently announced stabilization of the situation.
Slow growth lies ahead.
According to CBR experts, the recession in the Russian economy is a thing of the past.
"The index estimate of Russian GDP suggests that the recession is behind us, and slow economic growth is ahead," reads the Bank of Russia's bulletin What Trends Say.
The regulator raised its model estimate of GDP for the current quarter to 0.4%, and the estimate for the fourth quarter is 0.5%.
According to a representative of the Ministry of Economic Development, during the second quarter, the decline in GDP of the Russian Federation stopped in the second quarter, amounting to 0.2%.
In the second quarter, the seasonally adjusted decline in GDP was 0.2% quarter-on-quarter.
But during the quarter, the decline stopped: in April, it amounted to 0.2%, and in May and June, the change in GDP was in the range of 0-0.15, "RIA Novosti quotes a representative of the Ministry of Economic Development and Trade as saying.
The slowdown in the rate of decline of the Russian economy over the last five quarters indicates that the "bottom has been crossed."
Among other markers pointing to signs of recovery in the national economy, Bloomberg cites rising demand for electricity and rail transportation, and a revival of business.
Adjusting for the leap year, it is clear that the plus-1% growth in electricity consumption can be attributed by half to extra working hours.
Add to that the lower average annual temperature in the first quarter.
The next argument is growth in freight traffic, but it is difficult to get accurate data here, and plus or minus 0.5% of the semi-annual volume can also be explained by seasonality, "explains Kirill Yakovenko of ALOR BROKER.
But there are other, more obvious signs that the Russian economy is stabilizing.
For example, reducing price pressure.
In July, the consumer price index was 7.2%, compared to 15.6% in the same month last year.
Moreover, Rosstat has been recording deflation for the past two weeks.
Prices in Russia have fallen for the first time in five years.
If we look at the dynamics of the ruble exchange rate, which, although it showed strong fluctuations at the beginning of the year, has strengthened by 12% since the beginning of the year in August.
This is also one of the signs of recovery, which should be followed by indicators from the real sector of the economy, "emphasizes Yakovenko.
In addition, since April, there has been an increase in industrial production in the Russian Federation.
In June, the figure rose by 1.7%.
The rate of decline in foreign trade turnover is slowing from -32.8% in January 2016 to -20.7% in May.
Positive dynamics can also be seen in the labor market, where the unemployment rate fell to 5.4%.
It was only in September 2015 (5.2%) that it was lower.
Despite the favorable situation in the labor market, the issue of real disposable incomes of the population leaves much to be desired.
In year-on-year terms, the figure is down by 4.8%.
This factor could impede economic recovery, as household spending contributes significantly to GDP.
As a rule, their share in the structure of the economy exceeds 50%.
In addition to low consumer activity, the Bank of Russia's rigid policy can also be cited as a risk factor for economic growth.
The regulator is keeping the rate at 10.5%, which is not good for the real sector.
Underinvestment is also a negative factor, constraining the development of industrial capacity.
But on the whole, we can assume that by the end of the year, the rate of decline of the Russian economy will slow down to -0.5% compared to -3.7% in 2015, "says Irina Rogova, an analyst at Forex Club Group.
The process of naturalization of athletes, recently launched in Russian football and well established in winter sports at the Sochi Olympics, has not yet been so actively developed in summer sports.
If former foreigners are competing for Russia in the Rio Olympics, in most cases they are natives of countries - former republics of the Soviet Union.
On the other hand, in Rio de Janeiro we can observe the reverse process: quite a large number of Russians are performing under flags of other states.
In each case, the history of the change of nationality is different.
Some were taken to another country by their parents as children, leaving no choice.
Someone couldn't stand the competition for a place in the Russian national team.
And someone thought that the best conditions for development in sports would be created abroad.
Kommersant found at least 16 athletes who decided to change their Russian citizenship.
The 27-year-old's German passport says her name is Lisa Ryzih.
But before that, of course, she was Elizabeth.
She was born in 1988 in the city of Omsk.
Just four years later, when the Soviet Union collapsed, Lisa's parents decided to emigrate to Germany.
The girl had no choice.
There, she decided to follow in her older sister's footsteps and take up athletics.
Like her sister, Lisa opted for pole vault.
Had she stayed in Russia, she would hardly have been able to "dethrone" Elena Isinbayeva.
Unfortunately, at the Rio Olympics, Lisa will be the only fellow countrywoman, albeit a former one, in the pole vault.
Her best achievements in the sport were bronze at the 2010 European Championships and silver at the 2016 Continental Championships, which she won again in the absence of Elena Isinbayeva.
29-year-old Elena Pirozhkova was born in Novokuznetsk in 1986.
Her parents are evangelical religious propagandists.
In large part because of their faith, they left for the US when the girl was just three years old.
In addition to Elena, the family had eight other children.
They all lived in the small town of Greenfield, Massachusetts.
Lena started getting carried away with wrestling at school.
Showing good results, she moved to the city of Colorado Springs, where in the Training Center of Wrestling of the USA continued classes under the leadership of another former Russian, Vladislav Izboynikov.
At the 2012 Olympics in London, Elena lost in her first fight.
But at the World Cup that year, it was a victory.
Before that, by the way, she managed to win silver at the World Championships in 2010.
It was followed by a bronze in 2013 and a silver in 2014.
26-year-old Maria was born in Yaroslavl, where she first met synchronized swimming.
But to say that it was brought up by our coaches in Russia would be wrong.
Soon after, the girl's family decided to emigrate to the United States and settle in Colorado.
There Maria continued her studies.
Soon after, she was part of the US team and performed admirably at the Pan American Games.
It is clear that, on a serious international level, Russian synchronists cannot compete, but for America its performance is a ceiling.
Kristina Shaldybina received a new name, which sounds strange in Russian, at the age of 11, when her parents decided to continue the girl's training in rhythmic gymnastics across the ocean.
Until that point, the girl was engaged in her favorite sport in her native Yaroslavl.
After emigrating to the United States, she quickly became a member of that country's youth team, and later broke into the main national team.
At the Pan American Games, 19-year-old Kristen won gold and silver.
Of course, she didn't have to fight for first place on the world stage, but for the United States she organized a real breakthrough - she led the star-studded team to the Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.
Another of our former "artists" is Jana Berezko-Marggrander, who plays for the German national team.
Jana was born in Tolyatti.
In 2008, when the girl was 13 years old, the family decided to move to Germany, where the girl had better prospects of getting into the national team.
Soon after, she was representing her country at the 2012 Olympics in London.
There, however, Jana was able to take only 17th place, not enough to get into the final competition in the individual championship.
But two years earlier, she still managed to win a bronze medal at the Youth Olympic Games.
Another gymnast, only this time sporting, is Irina Sazonova.
If the emigration routes of the aforementioned athletes can be called standard, the choice of Irina's family is very unusual - Iceland.
Ira is a pupil of Volgograd sports school.
Naturally, in Iceland, she immediately became the champion of the country.
However, Ira still trains in Russia - specially comes home not to lose her skills.
She didn't perform as well in Rio as she would have liked.
The best place is 40 in the individual all-around.
There is very little information about the swimmer Maria Ugolkova in the Russian information space.
Maria has been living and training in Switzerland for a very long time.
However, for a long time she performed under the Russian flag, showing good results - there was even a national record in the 200 meters butterfly.
In 2015, she was granted Swiss citizenship and started performing under a red and white flag.
In Rio, her best performance was 14th place in the 4x100 medley relay.
In order to get to the Games, the girl launched a crowdfunding project, thanks to which she was able to raise about 6,000 francs, which enabled her to pay for the preparations for the Olympics.
31-year-old freestyle wrestler Adam Batirov practically spent his entire career under the Russian flag.
During this time the native of Khasavyurt managed to become a three-time prize-winner of the European championships, the champion of Russia, the master of sports of Russia of international class.
When he stopped being part of our national team, it was time to think about changing nationality.
For several years, the talented wrestler disappeared from the sporting scene.
The triumphant return took place at the 2016 Asian Championships - Batirov had already represented Bahrain, for which he won a gold medal and received a ticket to the Olympics in Rio.
Even less is known about another ex-Russian, Mikhail Kudinov, in his homeland than about the Swiss swimmer Maria Ugolkova.
The fact is that his parents emigrated from Vladivostok to New Zealand when the boy was very young.
It was there that Mikhail began to engage in artistic gymnastics.
He has not had much success at the international level.
In Rio, his best result was 40th place in qualifying on the parallel bars.
But for New Zealand, even getting to the Olympics in artistic gymnastics is a breakthrough.
When Nastya, born in Moscow in 1985, was just 9 years old, her family emigrated to Israel.
There, the girl continued her synchronized swimming lessons, showing high results at the national level.
In 2014, at the European Championships in Berlin, the girl took 6th place in synchronized swimming.
In a duet with Evgenia Tetelbaum, Anastasia took eighth place.
She was fifth in the solo program.
Like Anastasia, 23-year-old Dmitry Kreuter plays for the Israeli national team.
When the boy was only 6 years old, his mother decided to repatriate to Israel.
In 2009, at the age of 17, Dmitry had already become national champion.
In the same year, he won the World Youth Championship.
A year later, Kreuter also won gold at the Youth Olympic Games in Singapore.
In addition to the high jump, Dmitry is engaged in the long jump and triple jump.
31-year-old Albert - another native of Khasavyurt who after long performances for Russia made the decision to change the sports citizenship.
However, unlike Batirov, Albert chose Romania, which he will represent in Rio.
In Russia, he played for the School of Higher Sports Mastery of Krasnoyarsk, even becoming national champion in 2011.
28-year-old Oleg Antonov was born in Moscow to a member of the USSR volleyball team, Yaroslav Antonov.
Literally one year before the birth of his son, Yaroslav was recognized as the best volleyball player on the planet.
Soon he decided to continue his career in Italy.
The family stayed there permanently.
In 2015, as part of the national team, he won bronze at the European Championships held in his new homeland.
Khadzhiev was born in Chechnya in 1994 and found himself with his family in the midst of the war.
Ten years later, his parents decided to emigrate.
The original target was Norway, but it was not possible to get to this northern country - we had to go to France, to Nice.
There Zelimkhan continued to be trained in free-style wrestling.
Soon he won the world championship among juniors, and later qualified for participation in the Olympic Games.
In Rio, he will be the only representative of France in the wrestling tournament.
And again free-style wrestling, and again the former Russian.
This time it will be about a native of North Ossetia who emigrated to Spain - Taimuraz Friev.
At the end of December 2012, he was granted Spanish citizenship and now plays for the national team of that country.
Before that, however, the 30-year-old athlete managed to score high results in Russia as well.
He became the bronze medalist at the national championships in 2007 and 2008.
Tired of not getting into the national team, Taimuraz made a decision to change sports citizenship.
The last on our list is Arthur Biyarslanov, a Chechen boxer born in 1995 in Makhachkala, the capital of Dagestan.
When the boy was ten years old, his parents took the family via Azerbaijan to Canada.
There, Arthur, on the advice of his older brother, began to box.
Since then, Arthur has been Canadian champion three times, and in 2012 became world youth champion.
In 2015, Biyarslanov won gold at the Pan American Games, the first for his new homeland since 1975.
Head of the Executive Office of the President of the Russian Federation Anton Vaino.
On Friday, 12 August, Vladimir Putin appointed Anton Vaino as Chief of Staff of the Presidential Administration of Russia.
Previously, this post was held by Sergei Ivanov.
"The head of state appointed Anton Vaino as Chief of the Executive Office of the President of the Russian Federation by decree, relieving him of his post," reads the decree signed by Putin and published on the Kremlin website.
Since May 2012, Vaino has been Deputy Chief of the Executive Office of the President of the Russian Federation.
Anton Eduardovich Vaino was born on February 17, 1972 in Tallinn.
His father is Eduard Vaino, Chairman of the Cuba-Russia Business Council at the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Russian Federation and Vice President for External Relations and Shareholder Relations at AvtoVAZ.
His grandfather, Karl Vaino, was First Secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Estonia from 1978 to 1988.
In 1996, he graduated from the Moscow State Institute of International Relations of the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Faculty of International Relations.
From 1996 to 2001, he worked in the Russian Embassy in Japan, then in the Second Asia Department of the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
From 2002 to 2004, he held various positions in the Protocol Office of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2004 to 2007, he was Deputy Head of the Protocol and Organizational Department of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2007 to 2007, he was First Deputy Head of Protocol of the President of the Russian Federation.
From October 2007 to April 2008, he was Deputy Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
On April 25, 2008, he was appointed Head of Protocol of the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Deputy Head of the Government Staff of the Russian Federation.
Since December 27, 2011, he has been Minister of the Russian Federation and Chief of the Government Staff of the Russian Federation.
On May 22, 2012, he was appointed Deputy Head of the Executive Office of the President of the Russian Federation.
He is fluent in English and Japanese.
Active State Adviser of the Russian Federation, 1st Class (class rank assigned by Decree of the President of the Russian Federation of 22 January 2008)
Certificate of Honour of the President of the Russian Federation (16 February 2012) for services to the operation of the Government of the Russian Federation and many years of conscientious work.
Gratitude from the President of the Russian Federation (November 24, 2005) for his contribution to the preparation and holding of solemn events dedicated to the 60th anniversary of Victory in the Great Patriotic War.
He is married and has a son.
