I am referring, of course, to the ubiquitous craze that is PokÃ©mon Go, an app based on characters originally created for video games in the 1990 "s (which later spawned a series of cartoons, playing cards, and other offshoots).
Like many other pop cultural phenomena, all of this became obsolete a little before this new game became available in the US, Australia, and New Zealand in early July.
Launch in other countries at the time was delayed due to a massive response that overloaded servers.
In a matter of days, PokÃ©mon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
So how does it work?
In a nutshell, smartphone players go looking for PokÃ©mon, which are tracked by GPS and, once detected, can be 'photographed' (via a screenshot on your phone) or 'caught'.
A generation who played the game when they were younger has joined the craze, jumping off couches to search.
In the US, the game has led to a significant increase in the number of steps taken by the "average" person on a daily basis.
