Many health campaigns urging people to "find 30 minutes," "get off the couch," and "be active every day" have fallen on deaf ears, because most health messages are boring and delivered by people who look miserable.
Nevertheless, the importance of exercise should not be underestimated.
Those who exercise regularly reduce their chances of developing cancer or depression.
Physical activity helps with weight gain, high blood pressure, diabetes and a long list of benefits too long to list here.
But the beauty of PokÃ©mon Go is that it pulls people out into the street to do what they love.
Thus, three pillars of health are covered: movement, fresh air, and sunlight and joy.
Some people even make new friends on the hunt.
As usual, there are bored bores looking for something to complain about.
And yes, someone might stumble across the door.
So what?
The breakthrough has come.
After all, while smartphone apps such as Fitbit could previously track our physical activity, they didn't give us a reason to exercise, as this game does.
The novelty will wear off, and usage will wane over time.
However, because of Pokemon's success, there will be more games that combine apps and virtual reality with physical activity in the real world, helping many people on the hunt to be more active, fit and healthy.
