The HACCP system has been mandatory for food services for more than a year, but the majority of cafes and restaurants in St. Petersburg have not yet implemented it.
Inspections become more active, and businesses face fines of up to 1 million roubles.
For more than a year now, the Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points system (HACCP, in the Russian version of HACCP) - risk analysis and critical control points - has been mandatory for food producers and transporters, as well as for companies in the field of food services in Russia, as a member of the Customs Union (CU).
Business inspections by Rospotrebnadzor for compliance with these norms in St. Petersburg began in February 2015.
But so far, officials issue fines only for individual violations of the regulations (see "List of documents...").
Failure to comply with the regulations as a whole will cost the enterprise 600 thousand roubles for the first violation and 1 million roubles for the second.
HACCP was invented in the US in the 1960 "s as a risk-based system for handling and preventing food.
Back then, it was about food safety for astronauts.
The system is now used by all food companies, not only in the United States, but also in Canada and the European Union.
HACCP has been operating in the CU since February 2015.
Businesses had 4 years to develop and implement the system (the HACCP requirement appeared in the technical regulations of the CU in 2011).
However, both entrepreneurs and officials admit that most companies have not even heard of this rule.
Unfortunately, we have long been convinced that the norm applies only to food industries, not restaurateurs, explained Elena Tsereteli, Head of the Public Council.
Now everyone is trying to catch up.
