The ultimate vinyl consumer: who actually buys records?
Single middle-aged men love vinyl.
And until you rush to clog the comments section with crude insults under the pseudonym Not Alone Men of Medium Years, this claim is based on factual evidence.
According to YouGov, the much-discussed revival of records is driven not by a boom among the two-millennial generation, who want to be imbued with the novelty of a material object, but by middle-aged nostalgia.
Those who recently bought a vinyl album are more likely to be between the ages of 45 and 54, according to the data.
Moreover, those in the 18-24 age group are the least likely.
Nor is it simply an act of amateurs collecting - it has emotional significance: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their feelings to themselves (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy solitude (69% vs. 66%).
But are YouGov's results correct?
If this blog were a television news report, the camera would follow me as I walked down the middle of a busy Soho street, in a modest grey suit and gesturing violently before stopping, folding my hands and saying something impressive like, "So, let's see."
So, let's take a look.
While the heart of Soho is slowly losing its charm and grit - hotels, cafes, Paperchase stores are now filled with buildings once occupied by independent sellers - a few fantastic specialist music shops remain.
I would probably ask the camera to stop for the next scene, in which I stand close to various people in some of these stores and try to gauge their age and emotional state through observation.
Glasgow-born Stewart, 55, who I followed from Sister Ray (data count: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (data count: eight middle-aged men, one woman probably in her 20s), is in London for a half-day meeting and strolling the shops to take a few hours.
He's a collector, I ask?
"I think so," he says.
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These records, pictured above (he sent me an e-mail picture, I didn't follow him home), line the walls of his living room.
His reason for buying so many albums and singles stems partly from his disposable income: he can now buy records he couldn't afford when they first came out, and buy back items he sold when he was young and stranded.
"A lot of what I buy is the late 60s, the early 70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things for which I was probably too young to buy," he says.
He agrees that those who buy records are most likely introverts who like their own company, adding: "I don't smoke, I don't drink very much.
This is my flaw.
Wez, 25, who works for Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets fit the YouGov profile.
He did, however, notice a new wave of people influenced by the media hype, people who heard about the return and felt obliged to redeem their old records.
Judging by the conversations I have had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy back their records, "he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl renaissance artists of a certain age.
And what about the supposed emotional importance of the records?
One only has to spend a few seconds in a store like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a comfortable society to like-minded people.
According to Wez, some older customers, in particular, are offended by the cashless payment system.
Some vinyl lovers may feel the shock of the digital world and prefer to retreat into the constancy of familiar record envelopes, items that evoke memories of serene youth.
"I think sometimes it can be filling a void or having material things as a kind of comfort," says Wez.
As a collector myself, I have it, and I think a lot of people have it, too.
It's an easy way to get your head around it.
"We're like their social workers!" said a colleague from a stack of records.
An ICM poll in April found that almost 50% of people who bought a vinyl album last month had not yet listened to it.
The survey also found that 41% have a record player they never use, while 7% of those who buy vinyl don't have a record player.
At this stage of the news report, I would probably look seriously puzzled as I flicked through a stack of Bosanovo compilations.
The "trophy" aspect of the revival is what Johnny, 42, who works for Sounds of the Universe, has noticed (count: three middle-aged men).
"Someone came in recently and said," I don't have a record player, but I want to buy a Radiohead record so we can put it on our shelf, "" he says.
It's not a big percentage, but it definitely happens.
More of the stuff, less of the music.
We have people who say, "I don't have a record player."
These are younger people, not older people, in their early twenties, who are just getting acquainted with it.
Fopp, who now devotes almost the entire floor to vinyl, has a much more diverse audience when I arrive.
There are couples in their 70s, tourists taking pictures, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
Although the atmosphere is less laid-back than in the aforementioned stores - the latest synth and sex-pop Wild Beast, not jazz improvisation, makes its way through the speakers - it's nice to see diversity in its customers.
None of them look particularly lonely, but the excruciating psychological trauma is difficult to establish by standing next to someone for 30 seconds.
Eleanor, 27, walked around Fopp for a few minutes looking at the various records on sale.
She looks at the goods, not spends the money.
She doesn't earn much, she says, so collecting records isn't a good option.
It is expensive.
Listening to music on a computer or other device is easy, but the beauty of vinyl is... "she immerses herself in dreams with a sigh filled with love.
I don't know how to explain it - it's really unique.
My last stop is a store that is said to have spawned a new generation of vinyl lovers: Urban Fashionistas.
As I create the illusion of looking at denim tight shorts, I watch a group of teenage girls gather around a Polaroid camera every minute, before a father and his daughter discuss buying a Crosley player.
To the left is the staircase, the wall of which is stacked with records by Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac: a mix of modern style and classics, the obligatory records for any medium collection.
No one is looking - perhaps because they are just decoration, some so high on the wall that it would be impossible to touch them.
This is real "artistic vinyl."
But, given that any focus on these items could mean more money for the industry and send a few customers to the depths of Soho for a while longer, there is little to complain about.
Not surprisingly, the segment of the population that is more likely than most to have more time and money than most is the one that spends the most money on luxury items such as vinyl.
But while my findings suggest that YouGov's results are accurate, at least in Soho record stores, they do not rule out the huge number of female collectors and vinyl lovers that exist in reality, in record stores and on online forums.
These people probably work full-time in schools or offices.
But they clearly don't spend Thursday mornings strolling through record stores on Berwick Street, flipping through records and avoiding the glances of an unpleasant 30-year-old fake presenter who hangs over the shoulders of unsuspecting middle-aged men.
