French court rejects bid to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A French court has rejected a proposal by Calais authorities to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp where thousands of refugees live.
At a court hearing this week, Calais authorities argued that the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods ranging from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simple meals for a few euros in makeshift restaurants.
Calais Prefecture has argued that the sites should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes and because they carry fire and sanitation risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants were vital, saying the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups did not provide enough food for the camp's growing population.
They said makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to kick out the people running the 72 makeshift shops, but said the problems of the Calais prefecture were "fully understood."
Judge Jean-FranÃ§ois Molla said groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than simply feeding people who "live in extremely precarious conditions."
He said the spaces provided quiet meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places at risk of demolition was the camp's Jungle Book cafe for children, which is run for profit and offers 200 meals a day, English and French classes, and shelter counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
A letter sent to the Guardian said its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some as young as eight."
Two charities, Refugee Aid and L'Auberge des Migrants, estimated on Friday that the number of people in the Jungle camp had risen to more than 9,000 - the highest ever - after a surge in arrivals over the summer.
