Britain settle for silver in rugby sevens after Fiji masterclass allows them to take gold
Great Britain's impressive run in the Rugby Sevens was brought to a crushing halt at the final hurdle by Fiji in Thursday night's final when they were comprehensively beaten 43-7 at the Deodoro Stadium here in Rio.
Fiji gave a masterclass in ball possession, breakdown, evasion, support play, line running and brute force to win gold - their first Olympic medal of any colour.
Defeat came with not too much consolation in the form of silver - Britain's third of the day - and they could be proud of their efforts in the inaugural Olympic rugby sevens tournament, which saw them beat New Zealand, Argentina and South Africa en route.
The painful beating of the Boks, 7-5 in the semi-final earlier in the day, could come back to haunt them in the final.
But, against all odds, Fiji's form was the best of the 15-man squad.
It may be some consolation to Great Britain - but probably not - that at least one Briton will hang a gold medal around his neck tomorrow: Fiji's head coach, Ben Ryan, the former England boss from Wimbledon.
It's been a bit of a journey for Great Britain.
Eight years ago, under Ryan, they lost every game at the Adelaide Sevens.
Here, they lost just one.
These blows will hurt, but the progress is remarkable.
Fiji started superbly, repelling England's attempts to intercept the ball for fun.
It was like bumping into a column of moving buses for captain Tom Mitchell and company, and the World Series champions went up 5-0 when Osea Kolinisau dived into the corner.
With four minutes on the clock, Jerrir Tuwai added another down the right flank, which was converted.
12-0 and England barely touched the ball.
Mitchell's superb interception kept mountain man Leon Nakarawa from scoring the third, but it only held Fiji back.
In the seventh minute, Jasa Veremalua touched down in the right corner and England were 17-0 down.
Nakarawa added another after the restart and the clock was still more than a minute away... in the first half.
Vatemo Ravovo then broke through several more sluggish England interception attempts and stormed over the line to score.
The run led to 29-0 at the break.
It looked as if Fiji were born to play rugby sevens, while Great Britain are still mastering the craft.
Which is pretty much what it is.
Great Britain made massive substitutions at half-time and they clogged the Fijian dam... for all four minutes, which by first-half standards was good until Joshua Tuisova went over after some brilliant Fijian interplay.
Dan Norton grabbed a try for Great Britain with a touchdown in the left corner to make the score 36-7, but the game was long in the way of the South Sea Islanders, whose fans sang, waved flags and danced in the stands.
It was impossible not to admire Fiji's exhilarating approach.
Mata Viliame embellished a Fijian cake that did not need embellishment with another try in the dying seconds.
The whistle went, the Fijians embraced and Great Britain fell to the turf, utterly defeated.
Earlier in the day, Fiji defeated Japan 20-5 in their semi-final while Great Britain edged South Africa in a tense semi-final of one try each - the difference being the British record.
Kyle Brown put the Boks ahead in the first half but Dan Norton, with some superb footwork, broke the line and scored under the posts in the second half.
A brilliant late interception attempt from Marcus Watson, brother of England's 15-aside team, Anthony, secured the win - and ultimately the silver medal.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning inspired to rowing victory by coach's battle with cancer
There will be no more exciting gold at these Games, and that says something.
From the first movement to the last, 220 heavy climbs in history, Helen Glover and Heather Stanning found extra meaning to their golden moment at Estacio da Lagoa.
Although they were the two who pulled the oars, there were three voices in that boat, an echo of coach Robin Williams as they sought a second consecutive Olympic gold in the women's pairs, the first women in the annals of British sport to reach that height.
Their superiority was absolute, in the end it was their 39th unbeaten performance, again unprecedented.
What we see, two brilliant female athletes gliding across the surface with swan elegance, does not fully reflect the nature of the triumph.
Behind every rowing gold is a battalion of ready-made hands contributing to the incremental victories that matter, and there are no hands that have been more important than the hands of a coach who, 30 months ago when he was diagnosed with cancer, did not know if he would live to see this day.
As he said, it was a dangerous thing to do.
I had bladder cancer, which is one of the things they can operate on, and they did.
If they don't, it goes everywhere.
It could have been a pretty bad situation.
It changes your outlook a little bit.
Williams was diagnosed in December 2013.
The trio were fortunate that he could begin treatment early in 2014 in the off-season, keeping the schedule gap minimal if that may be the right expression in circumstances like these.
I needed to be paid, so I had to recover quickly.
It was a stimulus.
I was in the hospital and walking around the ward - 20 feet, 30 feet, 50 feet at a time, even though they were talking a few steps.
Here's how it starts.
Rowing itself is a journey, but it does make it a bit bigger.
In the moments after the victory, their first thoughts were for Williams, who had spent a nervous morning talking a little more than usual in an attempt to overcome his own emotions.
Stanning, a captain in the Artillery Regiment with service in Afghanistan behind her, said: "I've been an emotional wreck this week, maybe it's a bit too much, but it means so much."
It just confirms how much it means to me, how much Helen and I have worked, and Robin too.
It's been a fantastic three years with Helen and Robin.
Without Robin we would be nobody, so a huge thank you to him, he's the best coach in the world.
I couldn't have asked for a better training partner or a better coach.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning have not lost a race in five years.
This pair sets a tense rhythm that their competitors have never been able to match.
Even in the last 500 metres, when the New Zealand and Danish teams began to approach, Stanning and Glover had too much in reserve.
We were very much in phase.
Helen called out: 'Stay in the process, stay in the process.'
Now it is important not to get carried away.
We had a good start and at the same time we didn't try to do anything spectacular.
We weren't expecting fireworks today, we were just expecting to be able to race well and go out and win that race, which we did.
The couple will need a year to decide their future.
Glover needs to be at next month's wedding, her own with TV adventurer Steve Backshall.
Now she just wants to enjoy the moment.
I didn't want to say this was my last race.
That would mean too much pressure.
In London, it took about six months to realize that I was an Olympic champion.
It was all so new and I was so stressed.
It took about four minutes.
I feel so much better, "she said.
