Four people have been killed in a series of explosions at resorts in Thailand.
Several explosions struck southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed and 19 were wounded.
The epicenter of the explosions was the city of Hua Hin.
Ten foreigners, citizens of four countries, were among the victims, and no Russians were among them.
No terrorist group has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the Interior Ministry was quick to say that the Islamists were not involved.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary information from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military in charge of the country.
The attacks took place at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in Phuket and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
Since the military junta came to power in 2014, economic growth has fallen from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism has remained one of the few sectors to show growth.
In 2016, 14 million people have already visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of the attacks have already been detained, said Police Colonel Krisana Patanacharoen.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the Ministry of Internal Affairs of the country "is sure that they are not connected with international extremist groups."
It is too early to draw conclusions, "Mr Patanacharoen said.
But we do know that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, they are in fact local sabotage, and we are trying to identify those behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Thailand's Queen Sikrit.
With the Thai junta making defending the monarchy one of its top priorities, the incident is likely to be directed against it.
According to statements by Police General Sithichai Srispacharoenrath, the bombs were detonated remotely within half an hour of each other.
They were hidden inside trees on busy streets filled with tourists dining in restaurants.
It is already known that one of the four killed was a Thai girl selling street food.
The identities of the remaining victims are not yet known, but they are known to be residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai Police, they include four German citizens, three Dutch citizens, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of the Federal Tourism Agency reported.
