Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was entirely appointed by the military and had a significant role in electing the country's prime minister.
The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall that on May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the commander of the country's army, Prayuth Chan-ocha.
The move, he said, was prompted by the ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military established the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed a curfew and censorship, and dispersed protesters and the upper house of parliament.
