The authorities have tightened security in the capital and deployed military forces to protect demonstrators.
In Sukhoi Log, the development of conditions has begun.
Kommersant has learned that the government has been asked to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit, while retaining two key restrictions.
It is proposed to exclude from the auction companies where 25% or more is owned by foreigners and those bidders in whose capital there will be no minimum 25% state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players do not already risk taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources has submitted to the government a draft order and auction terms for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia, Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk Region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two Kommersant sources familiar with the situation told.
The draft was submitted on Wednesday evening, one of them said.
The Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment confirmed to Kommersant that the project has been submitted to the government.
A representative of Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr Khloponin, who oversees subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project had not yet been submitted to the official's office.
"The auction may be announced as early as August, immediately after the issuance of the government order, and, taking into account the deadline for the collection of applications from potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender may take place as early as October," the Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment said.
According to Kommersant, the project retained two key requirements for potential participants, which were spelled out in the version that was sent to the ministries and FOIVAM for approval in July (Kommersant has one).
The first is the presence of at least 25% of state participation in the capital of the bidders.
The second is denial of access to the auction to companies controlled by foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 about foreign investments in strategic companies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law mentioned in the draft, as Kommersant already wrote on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be allowed to participate in the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, as the Dry Log belongs to the subsoil of federal significance (reserves of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment confirmed that the draft "contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies," but declined to comment on the details until the government order.
The requirement for state participation in the capital of auction participants was put forward by Irkutsk Region, the Ministry of Natural Resources told Kommersant in December 2015 and was later confirmed by the Governor of the region, Sergei Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor, Sergei Eroshchenko, "who had agreements on investment projects with Rostec."
Kommersant's interlocutors do not specify who lobbied for the restriction on the admission of foreigners.
"But this is in the spirit of the times: not to give up control of the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions," says a Kommersant source familiar with the auction preparations.
On August 1, the head of the Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment, Sergei Donskoy, stated that foreigners "can join the consortium" if the bidders attract them "as a financial structure, as technological partners."
Kommersant's interlocutors consider it unlikely that the government will correct the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is considered to be a consortium of the largest gold miner in the Russian Federation, PJSC Polyus, controlled by Suleiman Kerimov's son Said, and Rostec.
According to Kommersant, in July, the partners established a joint venture called SL Gold, where Polyus holds 51% of the shares and Rostec's structure, RT-GR, has 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, while Polyus told Kommersant that it was "certainly interested in this asset" and had all the necessary expertise and resources for its development.
"But a final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the terms," Polyus added.
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision rests with the Russian government, Kommersant sources said.
Russia's GV Gold and Canada's Kinross, which is developing assets in Chukotka, have announced the possibility of participating in the development of Sukhoi Log, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
In December 2015, Sergei Kashuba, Head of the Union of Gold Producers of the Russian Federation, estimated Kommersant's investment in Sukhoi Log at $2.5-4 billion.
Most potential bidders are deterred not only by the volume of investments, but also by the complexity of the project: serious additional exploration of reserves and technologies for working with complex ores are needed, Kommersant's industry interlocutors explain.
On the pension market, the largest M & A deal has started - KIT Finance Pension Administrator has launched the process of merging four controlled NPFs.
As a result, an NPF with savings of about 373 billion roubles will be created on the basis of Gazfond Pension Savings.
Yesterday, the owner of 100% of the funds, LLC KIT Finance Pension Administrator, announced the launch of the procedure for merging four pension funds - KIT Finance, Promagrofond, Heritage, and Gazfond Pension Savings.
"The reorganization is being carried out in coordination with the Central Bank in compliance with the requirement not to worsen the terms of existing contracts," the company said in a statement.
The merger is being carried out on the basis of Gazfond Pension Savings.
According to the CEO of this NPF, Oleg Byaloshitsky, merging the funds allows to solve several tasks: expanding the geography of presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each fund, and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the estimated date for completion of the consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger of NPF Gazfond Pension Savings will become the largest player in the M & A market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of the merging funds exceeded 373 billion roubles.
According to the statements on the website of the funds, the beneficiaries of their owner - KIT Finance Pension Administrator - are currently Anatoly Gavrilenko (through controlled LLC owns 65%) and NPF Gazfond (35%).
However, the merger itself was launched much later than its competitors.
Thus, NPF Future, controlled by O1 Group, took over Stalfond at the beginning of this year.
Currently, this combined NPF is merging the Uralsib and Russian Standard funds.
"The merger into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary to solve structural problems," notes Nikolai Sidorov, CEO of NPF Future.
Active work on consolidation of funds has been underway in the Safmar pension group since April: NPFs European, Education and Science, and Regionfond are due to merge into NPF Safmar by the end of this year.
In 2017, NPF Doverie will join them.
"The merger of the funds will have the effect of strengthening control over risks, operational processes and costs," the Safmar pension group noted.
The pause in the merger of funds, which was sustained by the "KIT Finance Pension Administrator," can be caused by several reasons, experts point out.
Until recently, NPF could not buy back more than 40% of the issue of infrastructure bonds into which the group was actively placed.
After amendments were made to the resolution of the Central Bank in March of this year, there are no more such restrictions on a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator.
If necessary, the entire issue can be redeemed by one major player, "says Yuri Nogin, Director of ACRA's Financial Institutions Ratings Group.
Several heads of NPFs from the top-15 by assets cite the division of spheres of influence and, as a consequence, personnel appointments in a single fund, which the owners of the group had to approve, as another possible reason for the pause.
Anatoly Gavrilenko was unavailable for comment yesterday.
The Gazfond NPF also did not respond to Kommersant's request.
Although consolidation of funds is a time-consuming and expensive undertaking, it will be worthwhile over the long term.
According to Sergei Okolesnov, CEO of the consulting company Pension Partner, Gazfond Pension Savings has fewer outflows, and the merger will stabilize the base of the group's other funds.
At the same time, the more successful experience of NPFs KIT Finance and Promagrofond in building retail sales of OPS, as well as the use of more modern software, will be in demand.
The requirements of the Central Bank to the processes and personnel of NPFs are constantly growing, so it is impractical to duplicate the infrastructure on four funds under a single investment policy, according to Pavel Mitrofanov, Managing Director for Corporate Ratings at Expert RA.
"The effect of reducing duplicative functions will definitely cover the possible costs of the merger," Mr. Mitrofanov notes.
Sergei Okolesnov estimates the cost of merging the four funds at 30-50 million roubles.
"Expenditures on the maintenance of four funds of this size amount to about 400 million roubles per year, and in the medium term, consolidation will actually halve the budget," Mr. Okolesnov is convinced.
The kindest Disney film, "Pete and his Dragon," has been released in Russia.
Beautiful views of New Zealand, a delightful dragon, heartwarming history and country songs are enough to make you believe in old-fashioned magic again, says Elena Kravtsun.
The frightened baby was picked up by the dragon, who became both a gentle nanny and a devoted friend to the human cub.
Pete calls his buddy Elliot, after a puppy from a book of fairy tales, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in a hug.
Six years later, with his loincloth-clad face, he is no longer distinguishable from another clever woodpecker, Mowgli.
As it is, Pete is discovered by a redheaded female huntsman, Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while Gavin (Karl Urban), her husband's brother, is aggressively felling the forest.
Now she will not only have to believe in the dragon's existence, but also help save it.
Pete is undergoing an accelerated course of "being human" surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowboy shirts, have a moral code in their hearts, and smile more brightly than in any commercial.
No character looks or acts too terrible for the viewer to truly hate or fear.
Even Gavin, who has discovered a hunt for an atypical dweller in the forests under his control, is far from an incorrigible villain.
The huge fluffy dragon also turned out to be anything but scary, with a good bulldog snout, an airliner wing span, and the ability to become invisible.
The dragon purrs amusingly, purrs, even grunts and, fortunately, does not speak, but he always wants to be stroked, which makes him very different from all the well-known cinematic dragons.
Elliot's visual image and mannerisms provide such a high degree of emotional engagement that, in the most tense moments, not only the young audience, but also the adults begin to sob desperately into three streams.
Young Oakes Figley is also surprisingly good in the role of Pete, torn between a possible family and a real friend.
And Robert Redford masterfully portrays the canonical grandfather that literally every child would be happy to have.
How did director David Lowry manage to make a fantastically cute remake of the forgotten Disney film "Pete's Dragon" of 1977, mediocre from nose to tail and remembered only for a mix of animation and feature films, into this summer's most heartwarming film?
Nothing short of a miracle helped.
Lowry essentially took only two things from the original for his painting: an orphan Pete and a dragon.
Overboard were musical numbers and most of the odd jokes.
In this kind tale you can read features borrowed from "Bambi," "Alien," and many other sweet children's films.
Disney Studios continues to successfully expand the gallery of high-quality remakes of the 21st century.
Of course, "Pete and the Dragon" is not as stunningly beautiful as "The Jungle Book," and it lacks the cunning villain that Cate Blanchett turned out to be in the role of stepmother in the new "Cinderella."
But this naive film is no less successful in helping to believe in miracles and good in Disney's best traditions.
By the way, director Lowry will get the keys to Disney's magic castle once again - for an artistic film adaptation of the story of "Peter Pan."
The tandem of David Lowry and screenwriter Toby Halbrooks, who worked on "Pete and His Dragon," is part of an ambitious new project about an immature boy based on James Barry's fairy tale of the same name.
RBC journalist Alexander Sokolov to face new charges
Lawyers for RBC journalist Alexander Sokolov, accused of organizing the activities of an extremist structure, said that the prosecutor's office found flaws in their client's case.
We learned that the prosecutor's office made such a submission from investigators just yesterday.
We had planned to participate in a court hearing on the issue of restricting familiarization with the materials of the criminal case, but the hearing did not take place, and investigators informed us of the prosecutor's recommendation, "RBC quotes lawyer Olga Dinze as saying.
She said the prosecutor's office pointed out to investigators the discrepancy between the classification of the case and the materials collected.
Now investigators will have to close the gaps in the evidence base and bring a new charge against Alexander Sokolov.
Either another article of the Criminal Code (CC) will appear in the case, or it will remain the same, but with different arguments and new evidence, Ms. Dinze clarifies.
As Kommersant reported, Alexander Sokolov was arrested on July 29, 2015.
In June of this year, it was reported that the investigation excluded from the indictment of the RBC journalist the formulations on "unsettling the political situation towards instability" and "overthrowing the government by illegal means."
The correspondent of Kommersant Boscosport, Aleksandr Zilbert, lived the life of an Olympian in the Olympic Village, inspected the home of the Russian team, dined in the local canteen, and even passed the WADA test afterwards.
Life doesn't seem to stop there for a second.
Even at night.
The last starts sometimes end at midnight, after which the athletes need another hour and a half or two to return to the Olympic Village.
In addition, the settlement and eviction from the village is ongoing, as some athletes finish their performances and leave Brazil, and some, on the contrary, only arrive here.
Well, at 7: 30 a.m., the heads of all the Olympic delegations stretch into one of the temporary tents.
At these meetings, we usually discuss some operational everyday issues, "says Igor Kazikov, Head of the Sports Delegation of the Russian Olympic Team." Despite the fact that the house where ours are housed, consider it to be an exemplary one - it was one of the first to be put into operation and was shown to all the inspectors, even there are still some defects.
Now with hot water problems, then, sorry, with toilet bowls.
We fought for cleanliness for a long time.
At first, no one came to clean up.
Then the cleaners began to arrive, but only by spraying some substance on the floor, and that's it.
They have some innovative floors, you see.
They say you can't wash them humanely.
Yes, we know these floors - ordinary laminate flooring!
In general, we succeeded in changing the cleaning company and now everything is OK with it.
The Olympic Village is such a Yuzhnoe Butovo, a sleeping area surrounded on one side by mountains, on the other by an impressive moat, sometimes flooded with water.
Well, for reliability, there is also a two-meter iron fence along the entire perimeter, along which machine-gun men walk.
In total, the village can accommodate up to 17,000 people in 3,604 apartments located in 31 houses.
A huge Russian flag hangs on one of the 18-storey buildings - this house has been completely given to the needs of our national team.
Looking at the small foyer at the entrance, you can immediately identify what problems are probably the most pressing for the domestic team.
Two notices hang at the front desk: a printed "Please do not throw paper in the toilet!" and a handwritten "I will accept badges as a gift.
The counter itself is littered with booklets.
Their cheerful colouring contrasts with the titles of the brochures: "Information on infectious diseases for those travelling to Rio de Janeiro," "First aid in the event of drowning, ingestion of a foreign body into the airways, loss of consciousness - the stages of cardio-pulmonary resuscitation," "First aid in the event of burns, heat stroke, fractures and bleeding."
The text inside is, on the whole, encouraging.
For example: "Infection is accompanied by fever and subsequent cure.
But not everyone expects a favorable outcome.
Of course, the Russian team has a medical center at its disposal, which is ready at any moment to provide the residents of the house with qualified assistance, including relaxing and sports massage.
Opposite the medical centre is the very headquarters of our delegation.
Next to the door is an inspirational poster: "Against all odds, we will prevail!"
And, of course, poems:
All the arguments are absolute nonsense!
Only those who fear believe in them.
Let fewer of us, the sweeter the taste of victory, Russia not retreat, not break!
And for an even more uplifting message, hang an announcement: "Dear Brothers and Sisters!
With the blessing of His Holiness Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and All Russia, Archpriest Andrei Vladimirovich Alexeev is taking spiritual care of the athletes of the Russian Olympic team.
You can order a moleben and other services by phone...
In general, there is a Centre for Meditation and Religious Rites for members of all faiths in the village.
And Russians, it turns out, are in a privileged position - they have their own chapel.
Due to the congestion of the elevator from the ninth floor to the fourth floor, I decided to go down the stairs recommended for use during a fire.
And, in the darkness, I stumbled upon the bodies lying on it.
By all accounts, they were sleeping employees of a new cleaning company.
I suppose that at any moment they were ready to rush to wash the innovative floors and decided to arrange a quiet hour for themselves directly on the cold steps.
On the fourth floor, I was waiting for a meeting with an old acquaintance - Vitaly Fedorovich Dubko, the coach of our trampolines, who led them to Olympic gold 16 years ago in Sydney.
He and his pupil, European champion Yana Pavlova, kindly agreed to show their rooms.
By and large, there is nothing to complain about, - the honored coach of Russia shares his impressions. - We live by two, the beds, of course, are almost right up against each other, but it is not critical.
The bathroom is one for four, but spacious.
The wardrobe, of course, is funny, made of fabric, does not inspire confidence, but things can be put in.
"No, you guessed it, they've run out of tea!" says tennis player Svetlana Kuznetsova, whom I met in the main dining room.
It is called the main one if only because it has a space of 2.7 thousand square meters and is ready to receive 5 thousand visitors at the same time.
Here they give out 60 thousand servings a day absolutely free of charge.
Menu options include "Best of Brazil," "World Cuisines," "Asian Dishes," and "Pizza, Pasta."
The latter option, as I have seen, is very popular with our volleyball players.
At the same time, let's say, I did not find soup in any of the departments of the giant restaurant.
What soup? - Kuznetsova wonders. - There is no tea!
It's good to have a Chinese takeaway with me, custard.
And the kettle.
But in general, as you can see, the food on our courts is even worse.
There is at least something to choose from, despite the unbearable monotony.
I personally chose steamed cod and meatballs in tomato sauce.
Next to each dish is a plaque with its name in three languages - English, French and Portuguese - as well as an indication of the nutritional value of the product and the presence of allergens in it.
And quite, I must confess, it was edible.
I don't even understand why there is such a queue all the time at the local McDonald's.
Our best friends - representatives of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) - are waiting for the well-fed, relaxed and, one might say, "warm" athletes on their way out of the restaurant.
They lure you with a clever quiz, the winner of which gets a T-shirt.
They provoke, you might say!
To receive a gift, you must correctly answer at least eight out of ten questions.
There are questions in Russian! - the girl from WADA attacked me.
But she attacked the wrong man.
That is, I harnessed myself in a patriotic impulse, of course.
The situation worsened with the second question: "If I received a notification of doping control, should I immediately go to the doping control point?"
I settled on option B: "No - I have one hour."
I have lost my vigilance, so to speak.
I forgot that there is no room for complacency from WADA.
In general, you should report immediately.
Well, on the seventh stage of the quiz, my situation became quite critical.
For some reason, I thought that if I had difficulty following a balanced diet because of my busy schedule (which I do!), I could use supplements to get "extra nutrients to boost my performance."
No, they won't!
More precisely, the answer is formulated in such a way that it is not strictly prohibited, but strongly dissuades in a few sentences.
WADA is playing it dishonest!
How's it going, Russia? "the quiz's host mockingly asks.
There is nowhere to retreat - behind Efimov, Isinbayev and all our bloodied team.
So I concentrated and won the unfortunate t-shirt with my last effort.
Know, as the saying goes, our own!
In a triumphant mood, I wandered into the fitness centre next door.
I got carried away with counting the exercise machines.
I hit 250.
I was surprised to note that not a single Russian athlete was found in this pile of treadmills.
But maybe it is the right thing to do?
Let those who don't know how to play train!
But in a nearby polyclinic, one of our boys was sitting.
In line to see an ophthalmologist.
Don't worry, no shooter.
In the clinic, however, as in the rest of the village, wherever you spit, there is a device for distributing condoms.
It has an inspiring message on it: "Celebrate with the condom!"
All that remains is to twist the iron, which resembles the door lock handle, and the condom, made of natural latex from the Amazon, readily falls out of the apparatus.
I took one for myself, as a memento.
The athletes will not leave - they have brought 450 thousand of them.
There is a whole entertainment centre in the Olympic Village just for the celebration and idle pastime.
Next to it, just in case, stands an informative plaque reminding that the International Olympic Committee spends $3.25 million a day on athletes in various ways.
The center is awash with video games, billiards and tennis tables, table football and hockey, and some strange devices that look like video simulators.
What is this? - I ask a friend in the uniform of the Ukrainian national team, who is actively using a strange toy.
Of course, he could simply say that he does not want to talk to a man in the uniform of the Russian national team, and that's it.
Here, by the way, by some strange coincidence of circumstances, there is a ripple in the eyes from the boys in zhovto-blakite.
The most playing team, it turns out.
It takes at least three hours to walk around the whole village, visiting every nook and cranny of the village.
But if you walk, rather than ride in electric cars, you will find the home of the Canadian team with a moose at the entrance and a tent with a restoration bath, and a ticket office, and a laundry, and a dry cleaning, and a hairdresser, and a flower shop, and a shop with everyday goods, and a post office with unique stamps (but you still can't wait for the queue of Chinese philatelists), and a bank, and a lost property office, and a photo booth.
And late in the evening, exhausted, you will sit down by an olive tree hung with multicolored ribbons in memory of the athletes "friends and relatives who left the world.
To the accompaniment of a machine randomly spraying an insect-killing liquid, you will think of eternity.
That is about the Olympic movement.
Which in this village does not stop for a minute.
