The Spiritual Board of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the MRB ordered its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force young Tatars to "learn their native language."
The office says this "in no way infringes" on the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
Some mosques in Kazan complain that up to 60% of parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and Tatars themselves, do not understand Tatar.
The imams fear that their sermons in Tatar "will not reach the whole audience."
Yesterday, the plenum of the MRB of Tatarstan unanimously adopted a decision to conduct Friday sermons in mosques of the Republic only in Tatar.
As stated by the Mufti of Tatarstan, Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to "learn their native language."
"For those who will say that it is" difficult, "we intend to organize Tatar language lessons absolutely free of charge in every large mosque," Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that "the decision has already come into force" and today sermons in all mosques "should already be in the Tatar language."
He reminded that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with standard sermons in the Tatar language.
An imam who does not speak Tatar well enough "can thoroughly prepare for them."
The ROM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the Republic.
According to the mufti, Friday sermons in the districts are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques had previously used predominantly Russian.
In particular, as indicated by the mufti, this was practiced in Burnaevskaya Mosque, Zakabannaya Mosque and Eniler Mosque.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, the leadership sets a task that all students are proficient in both official languages of the Republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no question of any infringement of non-Tatar Muslims," Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, explaining that the sermon itself "is not mandatory, the main part of the prayer."
At the same time, the namaz itself will continue to be read in Arabic, and the mosques will retain lectures and lessons in Russian.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of pushing Tatar out of mosques.
Apart from Russian and Tatar, other languages, such as Uzbek or Tajik, are not used in sermons in the Republic, according to him.
The decision of the OMB was actively supported in the Executive Committee of the World Congress of the Tatars (WCT).
Head of the Executive Committee of the WCT, Rinat Zakirov, told Kommersant: "Mosques are an important part of our national life."
It would be sad if the Tatar language were to disappear from this sphere.
He noted that conducting sermons only in the Tatar language is "the will of the imams themselves," but the Executive Committee of the WCT "considers this to be the right thing to do."
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who conducted sermons in Russian, are ready to comply with the DUM's decision, but believe that parishioners will have difficulty understanding the clerics.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
Of course, it will be difficult for them.
"We will have to rebuild," says the imam of Burnaevskaya Mosque, Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, sermons in the Russian language are closer even to many Tatars, because "Russian in schools, in kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere initially."
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on Allah.
Allah will show the way out of this situation, "he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
They are Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
A lot of foreign students come to us: Africans, Arabs.
"That is why we switched to the Russian language four years ago," says the imam.
He believes that sermons in the Tatar language will "reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience."
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
Simply, the outcome of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
"For example, it will only be easier for me, because Tatar is my native language," Gabdulla Galiullin concluded.
The former director of the FSIN was put on trial
The Moscow Prosecutor's Office has approved an indictment in a criminal case investigated by the Main Investigations Directorate of the FSIN for embezzlement of budgetary funds allocated to the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
The former head of the prison agency, Alexander Reimer, and his deputy will appear in court, causing damage to the FSIN in the amount of more than 2.7 billion roubles.
The capital prosecutor's office referred to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court a criminal case against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia, Alexander Reimer, his former deputy, Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the Federal State Unitary Enterprise "Center for Information and Technical Support and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service" (FSUE CITOS), Viktor Oreschelenov.
Depending on their role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are charged by the Main Investigative Committee of the Russian Federation for Moscow under Article 285 (3) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers entailing grave consequences) and Article 159 (4) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using their official position, as part of an organized group, on an especially large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Article 222 (1) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the FSIN, in 2010-2012, these individuals fraudulently stole from the state treasury budgetary funds allocated to the FSIN to provide the agency with electronic monitoring systems for controlled persons, so-called electronic bracelets.
In order to steal budgetary money, the members of the group developed a scheme according to which an enterprise under their control, FSUE CITOS, with which the relevant government contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets," and sold at prices that were several times higher.
Despite the fact that the Federal State Unitary Enterprise TsITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, or facilities to accommodate production facilities that would allow for the creation of a complete cycle of production of "electronic bracelets," five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion roubles were concluded between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion roubles were deposited in the accounts of the Samara branch of the FSUE, of which 1.2 billion roubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of cash were personally received by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of his accomplices, the criminal case against whom has been separated into separate proceedings.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who was involved in the fraud, was found to have ammunition for an award pistol of unknown origin, which led to additional charges against him.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN filed a lawsuit against the accused for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion roubles.
