Russian Copper Company (RMK) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that RMK has undertaken to modernize one of the country's oldest and most environmentally "dirty" enterprises, the Karabash copper smelter.
The Karabash copper smelter was founded by a British joint-stock company headed by Leslie Urquhart in 1910.
In Soviet times, it was a significant industrial enterprise for the country's economy, and it actually provided for the life of the entire city.
In the 1990s, however, financial problems brought production to a halt, causing serious social problems in Karabash.
In 1998, it was decided to resume the operation of the Karabash copper smelter.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabash plant - the environmental one.
By the early 2000s, Karabash was already notorious as an ecological disaster zone.
The situation at Karabashmed began to change in 2004, after the enterprise was taken over by the Russian Copper Company.
The company began to modernize production, which gradually began to reduce the ecological burden on the environment.
This was recently noted by Boris Dubrovsky, Governor of Chelyabinsk Region, who visited Karabashmed in early July.
The head of the Southern Urals called the changes that have occurred to the enterprise since Karabashmed became a part of the RMK group "monumental."
The main modernization effort of Karabashmed in recent years has been the construction of a new sulphuric acid plant, which allows for the capture of up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to Vsevolod Levin, President of the Russian Copper Company, the volume of investments in this project amounted to about 7 billion roubles.
The next stage of modernization of CJSC "Karabashmed" is reconstruction of converter processing.
The replacement of three converters, dusters, and a gas pipeline is scheduled for the end of 2017.
The cost of the project is 2.5 billion roubles.
In addition, at the end of 2016, it is planned to launch a new industrial wastewater treatment plant worth 1 billion roubles.
In turn, the amount of taxes allocated to the budget of the city of Karabash will also increase.
For the entire duration of the Tominsk Mining and Processing Plant project - from the start of construction until the commissioning of the second phase - the federal treasury will receive 8.9 billion roubles.
And after commissioning of the mining and processing plant, tax revenues to budgets at all levels could amount to 80.9 billion roubles.
346.3 million roubles were transferred to the budgets of different levels during the year of production in Varnensky District.
And that's for the first year.
"The longer the enterprise successfully operates, the amount of contributions can be higher," Valery Ulanovsky added.
RMK clarified that in 2015, tax payments from Mikheevsky Mining and Processing Plant were close to RUB 1 billion.
However, the participation of RMK enterprises in the life and development of the areas where they operate is not limited to tax payments.
RMK's enterprises help to repair and maintain schools, kindergartens, sports facilities, build cultural and recreational facilities, and improve the territory.
In 2016, one of the largest social projects of the Russian Copper Company in Karabash was the overhaul, and in fact, almost complete reconstruction, of kindergarten No. 9 for 95 pupils.
The building, built in 1960, was in a state of disrepair.
