Bulgaria Shows Inflation for 1st Time in 8 Months
Inflation in Bulgaria was 1% month on month in July, national statistics show.
This is the highest figure in years (since June 2012) and the first above zero since October last year, when a positive 0.2% was recorded.
Average annual inflation, as measured by the CPI, for the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous 12 months (August 2014 - July 2015) was -0.8%.
The consumer price index in July 2016 compared to June 2016 was 101.0%, i.e. monthly inflation was 1.0%.
Inflation has been -0.2% since the beginning of the year (July 2016 compared to December 2015), and annual inflation in July 2016 compared to July 2015 was -0.2%.
In July 2016, compared to the previous month, the increase was observed in the price of the following groups of consumer goods: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%); transport (1.8%); recreation and culture (6.3%); restaurants and hotels (1.2%); other goods and services (0.3%).
Prices fell for clothing and footwear (2.2%); furniture, household appliances and routine maintenance (0.5%); and health (0.1%).
Prices remained at the same level as the previous month for alcoholic beverages and tobacco; housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels; communications systems; and education.
Snapchat's Anime Effect Criticized as Asian Caricature
Snapchat says the filter is inspired by anime, but some observers say it is racially insensitive.
With its "lens" tool, Snapchat allows some 150 million users a day to alter reality and play with individuality in ways that border on the absurd.
You can turn yourself into a pineapple, a dog, or a character in a Roy Lichtenstein painting.
The lenses are rough, feature-warping tools that create more than 30 million corrected selfies a day.
Any mistakes quickly become public knowledge.
Snapchat lenses have been criticized in the past when they have been accused of promoting dark facial skin or encouraging whitened faces as an ideal of beauty.
So when some users were offered a lens this week that gave them oblique eyes, crooked teeth and puffy cheeks, some critics deemed it a racist caricature of Asians - "yellow-faced."
And they wondered whether these recurring controversies point to the company's larger diversity problem.
On Wednesday, reports and outrage spread at The Verge and Motherboard, a day after Snapchat said it had removed the feature.
The company commented: 'The lens was designed as a homage to anime characters, not as a caricature of Asians.
But to experts who know about racism firsthand, the lens reminded them of offensive stereotypes in action.
Others rejected the anime comparison entirely.
In an email, Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweet about the photos was widely shared, said the lens was "offensive and embarrassing to say the least."
She added that "it's hard to argue with the comparison between a very crude caricature of Asians and the effects of the filter.
This shows that the filter is not just yellowface, but highly derogatory yellowface.
Snapchat is not the only company crossing these cultural bridges.
American culture seems to be engaged in an endless struggle for diversity and inclusion, from corporate boardrooms to Hollywood and the gadgets we all carry with us.
And Snapchat's huge audience of young people - who are more racially diverse than their elders - may mean that they are more likely to be expected to understand.
When one of Snapchat's lenses creates an image that is offensive to the user, Katie Zhu, 25, said in an interview on Thursday, "it's much harder to go unnoticed than it used to be."
On Thursday, Zhu, a product manager and engineer who works for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and encouraged others to do the same.
In an article for Medium and in a telephone interview, she said she believes racial tensions are the reason for Snapchat's lack of diversity in hiring.
Zhu criticized the company's predominantly white, all-male leadership and ended her post with the hashtag: # DeleteSnapchat.
As Zhu, herself a Chinese-American, wrote, "Either they didn't have enough non-white people on the staff to make these decisions, or they had non-white people working, but they didn't have positions where they could speak out safely and openly."
Other observers share her view, complaining that Snapchat has not answered most of her questions.
The company does not publish information on the representation of ethnic minorities in its staff, emphasizing its status as a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the racial origins of its staff, but according to a confidant, the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented populations and on actively trying to engage internal resources.
For her part, Zhu said she would keep her Snapchat account closed, adding, "I wonder if they really need more users like us to be able to say that it won't."
Military leaders misrepresented intelligence about ISIS, congressional panel says
Officials from the US Central Command altered intelligence reports to provide a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than events on the ground warranted, a congressional panel said in a report released Thursday.
An interim report by a task force set up by the Republican chairmen of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the Military Appropriations Subcommittee found "widespread discontent" among Central Command intelligence analysts, who said leaders were tweaking their assessments of American efforts to defeat the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, that oversees US military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence documents approved by Centcom's top command tended to present a more optimistic picture of US counterterrorism efforts than the actual evidence on the ground, and were consistently more optimistic than analysis provided by other intelligence agencies," the report said in a news release.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable: when a flawed analysis is presented to senior management, our military suffers," said Representative Ken Calvert, Republican of California.
Leadership problems at Centcom reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report details persistent shortcomings in Central Command's description and analysis of US efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
Although it does not contain definitive evidence that members of the Obama administration ordered the falsification of the reports, it claims that analysts felt that the Centcom leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"Throughout the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements, and congressional testimony were significantly more optimistic than actual events," the report said.
For example, a Centcom official has publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at recapturing Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
"After months of investigation, this is known for sure," Representative Mike Pompeo, Republican of Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the most senior US Central Command intelligence officials manipulated command intelligence documents to downplay the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans created the task force when they learned that analysts had expressed concern that intelligence about the Islamic State was being falsified.
As the investigation progresses, the report, released Thursday, will be followed by more detailed data.
An additional, incomplete investigation of Centcom's intelligence is being conducted by the Department of Defense's inspector general.
Democratic representatives on the House Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday, which are consistent with some of the findings of the Republican task force.
"Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an excessively closed process for making intelligence assessments about ISIS and Iraqi security forces," Representative Adam B. Schiff, the committee's top Democrat, said in a statement.
That process, Schiff said, "stalled the release of intelligence documents," damaged analysts "morale, and" did not adequately reflect divergent views. "
But Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House tried to force Centcom analysts to tailor their conclusions to a "predetermined or political interpretation."
The preliminary results of the congressional investigation were reported Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported the existence of an investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general, opened after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on the congressional report while the inspector general's investigation continues.
But he said that "experts sometimes disagree when interpreting complex data, and intelligence agencies and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital national security topics."
The implications of the investigation extend beyond the question of whether the US bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria (as a growing number of Defense Department officials now claim) is achieving its goal.
But last year's statements cast doubt on whether President Obama can rely on Central Command to provide accurate assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya, and other crisis spots.
Criticism of the intelligence on the Islamic State echoes the controversy of more than a decade ago, when a Centcom intelligence analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote a research paper arguing that the administration of President George Walker Bush, over the objections of many analysts, supported a small number of troops in Iraq without thinking about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the protest over intelligence on the Islamic State.
Last year, officials said, Hooker's team concluded that, despite public statements to the contrary, the airstrikes on Islamic State-owned refineries did not significantly worsen the terrorist group's financial position because it built temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market.
But the discovery was not spread beyond Central Command, the Times reported in September.
Centcom's then commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, came under criticism last year after Senate testimony that many lawmakers deemed overly optimistic about the war.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced in Central Command by Gen. Joseph L. Votel.
US Wins 4th Straight in Women's Field Hockey, Moving Closer to Crucial Battle with Britain
Katie Bam, who once scored three goals in a match that ended in a 6-1 victory over Japan, opened the scoring Thursday with the first two goals for the United States women's field hockey team as the Americans defeated India 3-0.
Five goals in two games should be a memorable achievement, but Bam, 27, says she is not sure if she would ever have done something like that.
"I won't use my mind," she said.
I'm not really one of those people who keeps track of their goals.
Here's what she knows: The Americans are 4-0 up in the Olympic tournament and are vying for top spot in their group with Britain, which remains unbeaten after losing 2-0 to Japan on Thursday.
The British and US teams will meet on Saturday in the last game of the first round.
Both teams qualify for the quarter-finals and the result will determine who finishes first in their six-team group and who finishes second.
The winner will avoid facing a strong Dutch team, the leaders of the other group, with a bit of weather when the quarter-finals begin.
But Saturday's game shows that the Americans have made a mess of it here, four years after finishing last among the 12 teams at the London Games.
Bam was on that team.
She grew up in Blue Bell, Pennsylvania, first picked up a field hockey stick when she was 3 (her twin older sisters played the sport at Drexel), and joined the national team at the age of 16, becoming its youngest-ever player.
She missed the 2008 Olympics when she failed to qualify for the final.
Then came 2012, when things didn't go well for her and her teammates.
The following year, Craig Parnham, an Englishman, was appointed coach, and things began to change.
"A cultural change, a psychological change, a change in physical fitness," Bam said.
In London, we didn't have the performance we have now.
We have completely changed our views.
On Thursday night, Bam opened the scoring in the first half with a free-kick from close range.
India came into the game without a single win in the tournament, but the team proved surprisingly tough and kept the score 1-0 until late in the third period, when Bam took the lead.
She made a long pass with the ball down the left side of the field, then spiraled into the middle and sent the ball abruptly into the goal, giving the Americans a 2-0 lead.
Melissa Gonzalez added the final goal midway through the fourth period.
The win was the first of the tournament for United States goalie Jackie Briggs, who missed one goal in each of the first three victories.
She's in shock.
Like Bam.
"We're in a good position right now," Parnham said, but how good it is depends on the outcome of Saturday's game.
Amid the Fury of the Olympics, the Zen of Trampoline
Wherever you are, whatever time it is, it is the Olympics.
Events in Rio de Janeiro seem immutable and inevitable, a frantic mix of competition and aspiration.
Like the Olympic torch itself, it is that burning torch that is passed from archer to swimmer, gymnast to triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or listen to your neighbors talk in turns in cafes and not hear about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
Then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a first-time Olympian with puffy cheeks, might well have been among the prime-time celebrities promoted by sponsors and life-affirming commercials if he had been a swimmer, a gymnast, or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, of Lake Forest, California, is fighting for gold in the Olympic trampoline competition.
The Olympic torch does not cover all events in the same way.
Further from the center, partly in the shadows, are those sports that are not universally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
Brass will always be with us, his long reign.
But if I am allowed to speak timidly in defense of my personal predilection, let me draw your attention to the modest charm of trampoline jumping.
Although trampoline has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it made its debut at the Sydney Games, over the past 16 years it has received so little recognition that many people I interviewed were unaware that it was an Olympic sport at all.
It can be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to compete, it never won a medal in trampoline, and its athletes did not make the finals until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians tend to share the men's award, while the Chinese and Canadians share the women's award.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie MacLennan of Canada will defend their London gold medals this year.
But trampoline has the charm of an outsider, not least because, for the unenlightened ear, it is more associated with a circus college than the Olympics.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, but just a down-to-earth enthusiast.
They do have comic potential - the caricature of endless jumps - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports that they mostly combine.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word "el trampolÃ­n," meaning "diving jump."
The hopefuls jump on a giant trampoline, soaring almost 30 feet into the air, and must perform a series of acrobatic tricks (turns, bends, and somersaults) before finally landing on their feet.
They are judged on performance, difficulty and "flight time," according to the official Olympic program.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic course is forward.
Medal hopefuls need to go further, faster, higher and higher in their pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish, sometimes back and forth, back and forth across the field.
They aim not only for the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in front of the television cameras, for another teasing milestone: a world or Olympic record.
This persistence is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and enough to bring even the viewer to tears.
But it is also, in my opinion, a little tiresome when watching the Games.
From it, trampoline jumping provides a respite.
The direction of the trampoline is upward.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she bounces, seemingly weightless, like an astronaut, flying up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
And, of course, they are not without competition or difficulty, but throughout the program there is no frantic zeal for the finish, no long jump, only a wondrous, graceful disappearance of time and gravity.
It is the closest to Zen Olympic sport.
The women's qualifying and then the final will take place on Friday afternoon, broadcast at 1pm Eastern European time; the men's on Saturday, also at 1pm.
NBC will air the finale as part of an afternoon program starting at 2 p.m. on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic madness, there is a quiet, beautiful moment to be seen in the public dumps.
And if consciousness-raising can be achieved only by subjecting male athletes to lust-inducing looks and objectification - as the United States men's gymnasts recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal - Dooley is just waiting for her new adoring crowd of fans.
"A generation is protesting" in Ethiopia, a long-time US ally
Violent Protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters have been fatally wounded in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of secession?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable countries, a firm ally of the West with rapidly growing economies.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to more and more of its territory.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets to demand radical political change.
Human rights advocates say the government's response has been brutal.
Witnesses claimed that police officers shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Videos from the protest sites, believed to have been shot late last year or earlier this year, show security officers beating young people with sticks as they were placed with their hands against a wall.
The top United Nations human rights official is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"It's always been difficult to keep this country from disintegrating, and it's going to be even harder," said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is Africa's second most populous country after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
America's military and intelligence services work closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia's economy is growing at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved considerably - there is even a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
And its streets are typically quiet, safe, and clean.
But Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations routinely cite government repression - and opposition within the state was stifled by effectively silencing dissidents.
Many have been exiled, imprisoned, killed or driven to remote deserts.
But that could change.
"If people are constantly suppressed and left with no choice but to protest, there will be a rebellion," said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All the young people are protesting.
A generation is protesting.
Complaints range from land use to the government coalition's power grab.
After a widely criticized election last year, the government party and its allies completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; fighting over that uncertain, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less wiped out in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings that have been simmering for years are flaring up now.
The first, seemingly harmless: smartphones.
In the last couple of years alone, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social media, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace and Internet service has improved.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as is often the case, especially during protests, many people still find it possible to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that was how they organized themselves to protest.
Second, there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, Ethiopia's two largest ethnic groups.
The Oromos and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amhara from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands flourished in politics and business, exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslim and live in low-lying areas.
But that, too, is changing.
"We will work together under one umbrella," said Mulatu Gemechu, the Oromo leader.
The largest protests took place in the Amhara and Oromo districts.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 per cent of the population and controls the military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at detecting early signals of discontent and using intelligence to gather data and neutralize opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, emerged from nowhere to take Meles's place.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed as a result.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands protested against what analysts said appeared to be an election that the government rigged and then rigged.
In the ensuing crackdown, many protesters were killed, though in smaller numbers than in recent months, and the period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for forward-looking infrastructure development, such as a new long-distance train, and significant progress in poverty reduction.
But this has clearly not stopped the rise of internal discontent with Ethiopia's government.
And it is taking a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tigray hatred on social media is becoming all-pervasive.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The US government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, though it recently announced that it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand it does not want its ally to lose strength in an already unstable region.
"It's going to be hard to walk that tightrope," Abdi said.
Donald Trump explains his claim that ISIS was founded by Obama as "sarcasm"
Donald J. Trump tried to play down the latest controversy engulfing his campaign on Friday, claiming he was joking when he claimed several times this week that President Obama and Hillary Clinton were the "founders" of the Islamic State terrorist group.
The clarification raised new questions about the Republican presidential candidate's ability to communicate clearly to the American people.
It also put his deputies, who had tried to protect him during a period of unrest, in an awkward position, having to explain statements that he probably did not mean.
After making the suggestion at the convention on Wednesday night, Trump insisted strongly on his claim on Thursday, repeating in interviews that he did mean to say that the president and Clinton had founded ISIS.
But in a Twitter post in the early hours of Friday morning, Trump wrote that he was just being caustic.
The post was the exact opposite of an assertion made just a day earlier, when Trump said in several interviews that he was absolutely serious about his accusation.
When conservative radio host Hugh Hewitt tried to help Trump soften the remark by reminding him that Obama wants to destroy ISIS, the Republican presidential candidate did not seize the opportunity.
The latest scandal erupted as Trump tried to refocus his campaign on the economy amid declining ratings.
Trump and Clinton delivered competing speeches on the economy in Michigan this week.
On Friday, Trump tried again to return to the topic.
Taking to Twitter again, he warned that Clinton's plans would lead to higher taxes and said he found her speech boring.
Trump has used sarcasm as an excuse in the past.
In late July, after drawing widespread criticism by suggesting that the Russians should hack Clinton's emails, he later clarified his remarks by saying, "Of course I'm kidding."
This approach allows Trump to go beyond what is permissible in a political speech and take his words back if necessary.
"I think it's his way of testing certain messages that resonate with his fans, seeing how they work, and then" explaining "them one way or the other depending on the reaction," said Ruth Sherman, a communications expert who analyzed the language of both candidates.
But I also think he is careful about what he says and knows that it is vague enough to be interpreted differently.
Instead of softening his language for the broader electorate, Trump has taken an even more acrimonious tone in recent days as his approval ratings continue to fall.
A new NBC / Wall Street Journal / Marist poll released Friday showed Trump trailing Clinton by large margins in North Carolina, Virginia and Colorado and trailing her in Florida.
While Trump tends not to apologize for provocative things he says, he often accuses his critics of misinterpreting his words and misunderstanding his sense of humor.
But as Trump has come under intense scrutiny in the final months of the presidential campaign, his jokes have embarrassed his loyal allies, who have had to publicly support him, no matter how provocative his remarks.
Rudolph W. Giuliani, the former mayor of New York who is one of Trump's best-known surrogates, went to great lengths to defend the candidate in an interview with CNN on Thursday.
"I think what he's saying is an acceptable political comment," Giuliani said when asked about the veracity of Trump's claim that Obama and Clinton founded the Islamic State.
It is true in the sense that before Obama, ISIS was an almost unknown small organization, he called it a no-threat, totally unfair organization, and that is why it happened, because he withdrew troops from Iraq.
Most average Republicans believe that the Obama administration, under which Clinton served as secretary of state, allowed ISIS to develop because it failed to deal firmly with the Middle East.
Before Friday's rally in Pennsylvania, Trump continued on Twitter to attack the media for blurring his every word and being biased against him.
He scoffed at the "poor hapless" TV pundits trying to figure him out and said: "They're weak!"
Some Democrats scoffed at Trump's excuses as further evidence that he is unfit to be president.
Once-Displaced Cafe Returns to Greenpoint
Verb Cafe was a shabby, cash-only space in Williamsburg that had no Wi-Fi but served good coffee for 15 years.
Naturally, she was forced out of her Bedford Avenue showroom.
The Soup Cherie store, which took Verb's place in the summer of 2014, sells cupcake-shaped soap.
Locals mourned it as the latest loss in a rejuvenating city.
Artist Molly Crabble wrote on Twitter: 'New York is changing all the time, I know, but I still can't believe CBGB is dead, Chelsea Hotel is ruined and Verb is now a soap shop.'
But while New York City is constantly changing, it is also renewing itself.
The revived Verb Cafe opened last November in Greenpoint, less than a mile north of its original location.
The new Verb has Wi-Fi and accepts credit cards, but there are still some of the same employees and a similar simple atmosphere.
And the coffee is still good.
At the head of the new Verb is Cisco Rodriguez, a longtime employee of the old coffee shop who is the owner and general manager of the new location.
He joined Verb in 2001 and was there until the end.
When a client offered to sponsor him in a new location, he said he would be happy to do so.
Rodriguez, 36, left much to the imagination.
Verb works with the same bagel distributor and bought the same model of coffee machine.
It even has chandeliers from the old Verb.
But Rodriguez said he also wanted to experiment.
He offered new dishes.
Bacon, egg and cheese sandwiches are on the menu, and toppings of capers or fried onions are available.
There are brown rice dishes.
The cafe no longer serves beer, but now prepares freshly squeezed juices.
Nine months later, Rodriguez said he noticed a steady stream of old regular customers.
"A lot of former customers were also squeezed out of Williamsburg," he said.
On a recent Sunday, Rebecca Oliveira was one of those customers.
Oliveira, 34, previously lived in Williamsburg and frequented Verb.
Even after she moved to Greenpoint, she still went there.
After Verb closed, she said she stopped drinking coffee for a while.
"I realized that it was the coffee and the atmosphere that impressed me at Verb," she said.
Now she drinks coffee again, though that day she ordered blended tea instead of the usual ice coffee, another novelty.
Tom Rosenthal, another longtime client, has been a loyal visitor to Verb since 2003.
He would come in before work and order invariably the same thing.
"At fifteen minutes eight, every day, like clockwork, I would come in and they would make my bagel with butter and all the fillings for me," he said.
Rodriguez said he wanted to experiment and introduced new dishes to the menu.
Today, Rosenthal still makes the usual order, but one day he'll change something with bacon, egg, or cheese on a bagel with all the fillings.
Rodriguez said he was not offended that the soap store once took over the old place.
Moreover, the owners of Soup Cherie offered to make special soap for Verb, using cold coffee from the cafe as an ingredient.
"I think we might accept their offer," Rodriguez said.
Regular residents of Greenpoint of Polish origin also flocked to the cafe.
One of these new customers translated the menu into Polish, and Rodriguez said he plans to find a place for him in the window to make his new neighbors feel welcome.
The new location has other benefits.
The local juice outlet plans to bottle and sell cold-brewed coffee.
There is a chance that the coffee shop will be annexed to an adjacent building.
For many customers, it is enough that the new Verb will include their favorite dishes on the menu.
Joseph Whitt was a regular customer and said he was devastated when they closed.
When the coffee shop opened at its new location, Whitt said that when he walked in and ordered a cup of coffee, it felt like he was back home.
"I've wanted to smell it for a long time," he admitted.
Depression's Depressive Food in "Dense Meal"
In March 1933, shortly after ascending to the presidency, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down to lunch in the Oval Office.
As a gourmand, President Roosevelt loved fashionable Fifth Avenue dishes such as foie gras and Meryland tortoise soup.
His menu that day was more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and, for dessert, prune pudding.
"It was an act of culinary solidarity with the people who were suffering," Jane Ziegelman said.
Her husband, Andrew Coe, added, "It was also a message to Americans about how to eat."
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are food historians.
Coe's most recent book, "Chinese Ragu," was about Chinese cuisine in America, and Ziegelman told the story of living in a rental apartment on the Lower East Side through food in her book "97 Fruit Garden Street House."
Their new collaborative work, "A Dense Meal," to be published Tuesday by Harper, is a history of American food during the Great Depression.
Showing some culinary solidarity of their own, they met a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a tiny, simple eatery in the Flatiron district that has been open since 1929, the year of the stock market crash.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered cream cheese and a sandwich with slices of olives, while Coe, 57, picked up turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetable mixture.
When a reporter ordered a meat roll, the couple found it a good starting point for a discussion about Depression-era food.
"There was a lot of demand for the rolls," Ms. Ziegelman said.
There was a peanut roll, a liver roll, a bean roll.
They were made from the main ingredient and cheap products that allowed the ingredient to stretch.
Imagine eating as many peanuts as you need for dinner.
Coe grinned.
"He must have had a stone in his stomach," he said.
In the years before the Depression, the American table, especially in rural areas, was a buffet.
Groups of women cooked for male farm workers, and freshly baked pie was served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. "A Dense Meal" describes how the country coped with suddenly ceasing to be a land of plenty.
"It was a time when food became a central, challenging topic for Americans," Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Equally challenging was the new budget diet: mysterious dishes like rolls and casseroles became staples; casseroles were "a great way to recycle leftovers," Ziegelman noted, because chefs could hide unappetising ingredients under a thick layer of sauce.
Fresh fruit has been replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, for years the mainstay of American food, has become a frugally distributed luxury.
People tried strange mixtures because energy and nutritional value became more important than taste and even culinary common sense.
While researching for a book that includes recipes, Ziegelman prepared a dish of the era: baked onions stuffed with peanut butter.
"This addition to the dinner table has not been a success," Coe said.
Ziegelman added, "It was very strange."
Peanut butter is completely unsuitable for baked onions.
This was typical of many household recipes.
As never before, and never since, home economists - including Louise Stanley, head of the federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - have managed the country's eating habits.
Publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they advised women to become "budget makers," take up the challenge and transform burdened spaghetti with carrots into tasty dishes.
"A Dense Meal" is a feast of curious historical facts.
Tales of the government's response to starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's "let them eat pies" attitude, are particularly piquant.
Publicly extolling the simple Iowa farm bill of his childhood, he ate like the sophisticated millionaire he had become.
"He liked continental cuisine, like fish with cucumber sauce," Coe said.
He ate almost in a gold-plated dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was fantastically detached from reality.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake had his wife, Eleanor, not advised him to set an example with his own stomach.
According to the book, Eleanor Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who had no interest in taste at all, which led the White House to "eat not only the saddest food in Washington, but sometimes the most hideously cooked."
Many of the Depression-era culinary tricks were forgotten once the country got back on its feet.
Their legacy is our constant focus on calories and nutrition, Ziegelman says, and on how science has been used in cooking.
The couple say that while writing the book, they gained a better understanding of Ziegelman's mother's eating habits - that she couldn't throw away food, for example.
"She had a serious fear of food neglect," Coe said.
Ziegelman recalls: "She was absolutely poisoning people."
There was one nasty incident with profiteers.
When the plates at Eisenberg's were empty, he and Coe took out a dessert they had made at home: the prune dessert that President Roosevelt ate for lunch.
"It's called prune mousse," Ms. Ziegelman said, adding that it was a common trick to give modest recipes catchy names.
There was no whipped cream, only prunes, a little flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly dipped the spoon into a viscous, brown, sticky substance.
Surprisingly, it wasn't bad.
Coe asked for supplements twice.
In the voice of a confident budgeter, he told his wife, "A little chopped walnuts wouldn't hurt."
