Hillary Clinton on Friday released her 2015 tax returns, which showed that the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband had $10.75 million in income this year and paid an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 percent.
In 2015, the Clintons received $1 million in charitable contributions, mostly to the Clinton Foundation, former President Bill Clinton received about $5.3 million in speaking fees, and the former secretary of state reported income of $3 million from publisher Simon & Schuster for her book on her tenure at the State Department.
Clinton's would-be vice president, U.S. Senator Tim Kaine of Virginia, along with his wife, Anna Holton, released 10 years of tax returns.
In 2015, they paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 percent.
"Hillary Clinton and Tim Kaine continue to set the standard for financial transparency," Clinton campaign adviser Jennifer Palmieri said in a statement.
In stark contrast, Donald Trump is hiding behind bogus excuses and reneging on his past promises to release his tax returns.
It is common for US presidential candidates to publish their tax returns, even though the law does not require them to do so.
New York businessman Trump and his lawyers cited a Internal Revenue Service audit as the reason for his refusal to release his tax returns.
"Your move," Clinton campaign adviser Ian Sams tweeted, referring to the Democratic nominee's declarations.
On Thursday, Trump's special counsel, Michael Cohen, told CNN that he would not allow Trump to release them until the reviews were complete.
