Chili powder condoms and fireworks boost protection of Tanzania's elephants
Conservationists in Tanzania are using an unconventional way to stop elephants from wandering into human settlements - throwing condoms filled with chilli powder at them.
The method proved effective, and the Honeyguide Foundation, which came up with the idea a few years ago, together with the US Committee for the Conservation of Nature, took it upon themselves to promote it by training volunteers in villages in northern Tanzania to use a non-violent, four-step way to protect their homes and crops without harming animals.
Previously, many used spears to defend themselves.
Friday will be World Elephant Day, dedicated to animal welfare.
"Since we invented the toolkit... we have seen a change in attitudes within these communities, making them much more confident that they can keep elephants out of their fields without harming elephants," Honeyguide executive director Damian Bell said in a statement.
The first two steps consist of lighting the torch in front of the trespassing elephant and sounding the horn.
If he is not deterred, a so-called "chili cloud" is thrown.
The chilli powder, mixed with soil, is placed with a flake in a condom, and its end is twisted, with only a wick left outside.
When lit, the condom bursts with a bang, spraying a fine dust of chilli powder in the air.
One blow is usually enough to turn an elephant in the other direction.
The last resort is a launcher that fires Roman candles into the air, producing a loud, bright explosion.
