Adblock Plus, Facebook play cat-and-mouse game over ad blocking
For companies that make money from online advertising, trying to circumvent ad-blocking software is a "cat-and-mouse game," according to one of the companies that makes the software.
On Thursday, just a couple of days after Facebook announced that it was going to block ad blockers on its desktop version of the site, Adblock Plus posted a blog post saying that users could update their filters in the program to block ads on the social network again.
On Tuesday, Facebook announced that the desktop version of the site will change the layout around its ads to make it harder for ad blockers to recognize which parts of the page are ads.
But Adblock now says it was able to get around the new code.
In a blog post, Adblock spokesman Ben Williams wrote that "this kind of mutual struggle between the open-source ad blocking community and those who try to circumvent it has been going on since the invention of ad blocking," and it is possible that Facebook will present its own solution soon.
The fact that the world's largest social network has entered the fray is a clear sign of just how big an issue ad blockers have become for the industry.
Worldwide, some 200 million people use ad blockers, according to a study last year by Pagefair and Adobe; almost four times as many used such software in 2013.
With 1.3 billion daily active users accessing Facebook via mobile devices, mobile advertising now accounts for 84 percent of Facebook's ad revenue.
However, the company is hunting for desktop ad blockers because mobile ad blockers are ineffective in Facebook's mobile apps for the social network and Instagram, according to a spokesman.
Still, desktop advertising is a lucrative enough item that Facebook considers such a move a profitable investment.
Also on Thursday, Facebook announced that it would update its "ad preferences" tool to give people more control over how ads are targeted at them.
On Thursday, Facebook said Adblock's new filters are worrisome because they will also block some non-advertising content on the site.
"This will not be a positive experience for people and we plan to address this issue," a Facebook spokesperson said in an official email.
Ad blockers are a blunt tool, so we instead focused on creating tools like Ad Preferences to put control in people's hands.
