NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to a new NASA climate model.
Scientists at Nasa's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore Venus's past using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and carbon-dioxide-saturated atmosphere, could ever have had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus's slow rotation rate is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulations suggest that Venus may have had a rarefied Earth-like atmosphere and still rotated slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had more dry regions than Earth, but once had enough water and geographic variability to support life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus substitutes its daytime side of the sun for almost two months at a time," GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet's surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that acts as an umbrella to protect the planet's surface from much of the sun's heat.
The result is an average climate temperature that, surprisingly, is a few degrees cooler than today's Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by planetary scientists.
Although Venus may once have been habitable, it has been exposed for several billion years to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, all that remained was a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a lethal greenhouse effect - that is, Venus as we know it today.
Researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
