Kepler measures rotation rates of stars in Pleiades cluster
The latest mission by the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the spin rates of the stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in a cluster spin at different speeds, as well as how rotation periods relate to planet formation.
"By comparing our results with other star clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system," Louise Rebull, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology, said in a press release.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are just reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They are spinning as fast as ever.
At their peak spin speeds, these maturing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
By traveling through the stars "magnetic fields, these winds have a retarding effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its spin rate begins to slow.
Kepler measures the spin rate of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots - such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of spin rates suggests that more massive stars spin more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull likens the stars to dancers: the larger ones make pirouettes more slowly than the smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades' ballet, we see that those that spin slowly tend to be more massive, whereas those that spin faster tend to be very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with their rotation speeds.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older," Rebull said.
We still have much to learn about how, where, and why stars slow down their rotation and hang up their "dance shoes," figuratively speaking.
Rebull and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the spin rates of the Pleiades in three new papers soon to be published in the Astronomical Journal.
