Sandwiched between Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered mightily during the long struggle against apartheid.
Nevertheless, since gaining independence from South Africa in 1990, the country of 2.4 million people has made tremendous strides, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is the government's emphasis on education.
While people in developed countries take for granted free primary and secondary education, in many poor countries, secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce tuition fees to "recover costs."
In Namibia, however, primary education is free.
Moreover, since 2015, secondary education has also become free.
The authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases by 97% over the past decade.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, the standard measure of income inequality, has fallen by 15 points.
Back then, 23 years ago, that figure was one of the highest in the world.
And the poverty rate has fallen from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (on less than $1.90 a day) has also declined, from almost 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest free-speech rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country is well ahead of the United States and other rich nations.
Moreover, the country has a favorable rating - one of the highest in Africa - in the Corruption Perceptions Index, which is compiled by human rights defenders from Transparency International.
Even now, when commodity prices are falling, Namibia has managed to maintain high growth rates.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is around 25%, which is less than one-third of the level of debt in the US and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia also has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional estimations, is still quite high, at almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV / AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is an upper-middle-income country, but the authorities insist that the country is in fact a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the challenges inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
Isolated nomadic hunter-gatherer tribes live in the deserts of the country and must somehow be integrated into modern society without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter-century ago is no easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: like any other country in the world, it is facing the consequences of climate change.
Namibia has not given up, however, and is addressing the challenges it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities set about creating a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
Remarkably, rival political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides low-cost health care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
Approximately 15-20% of visitors to health facilities in northern Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
Namibians understood that neighbors were not chosen, so they decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - sharing scarce water resources, participating in regional health projects, encouraging investment, and exchanging students.
Moreover, Namibia's government has rightly recognized that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, enriching the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the revenues from Namibia's natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and productive capacity.
They also recognize that it would be irresponsible not to seek to maximize profits from the sale of the country's resources, and are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to ensure that this is the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, which is why strong government support for free speech is so important.
As the head of state, Hage Geingob, has noted, the media often say things that he does not like.
But after the struggle for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must protect its liberties, the president says.
Not all of Namibia's key resources are finite.
Some - such as fishing - are renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year, more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even countries that begin with serious flaws - racism, colonialism, inequality, and underdevelopment - can embark on the path to shared prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and emulation.
Many have heard about the "Gold of Varna," the oldest gold objects created by man (4600-4200 BC).
It was probably the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavation of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artefacts - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms - were found.
In one grave alone, known as Grave No. 43, 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were recovered.
However, the official status of the world's oldest gold may soon be transferred to the pristine-looking beads found by archaeologists in July of this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunatsite.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Yunatsite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatsite in the Pazardzhik district.
The beads are a gold band wrapped in a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, the head of excavations at Tell Yunatsite, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it was at least 200 years older than the gold of Varna.
The treasures of Varna, let us recall, date from about the same period, 4600-4200 BC.
Technologies to date metal with impeccable accuracy do not currently exist.
Where is the certainty about which gold is more ancient?
Obviously, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am absolutely sure that Yunatsite's gold is older than Varna's."
This is an extremely important find: it looks tiny, but it is big enough to take its rightful place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-examine the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the beads as accurately as possible.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatsite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Today Tell Yunatsite is considered to be the oldest "city" in Europe.
Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, metal processing flourished in the region, from mastering the first metallurgical skills to creating a full-fledged industry.
In Russian historiography, there is a special name for this archaeological community: the Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban settlements began to emerge around metal processing centers.
They are now called the oldest cities in Europe.
Tell Yunatsite is probably the oldest of these, as artefacts dating back to 4900 BC have been found here.
I would call Tell Yunatsite a prototype of a modern city, even though it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This place is a thousand years older than Schumer," Boyadzhiev says, referring to the conventional wisdom that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia, modern Iraq.
It was there that the first cities in the familiar sense of the word arose.
Excavations of Tell Yunatsite have been underway since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about one-third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three metres in height, have been found.
Little remains of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists can clearly distinguish between streets, public buildings, dense urban buildings, a "business center" and residential suburbs.
Tell Yunatsite is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay bird figurines have been found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of calm, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
The "Bird City" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes that came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but horses and weapons.
The three-metre-high fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: the remains of elderly people, women and children were found inside the houses with marks of wounds inflicted by axes.
New discoveries and new facts emerge every year, changing the conventional wisdom about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe born in the Balkans.
A powerful impetus in the search for this civilization was the "gold of Varna," found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that Varna's golden luxury should have been preceded by something - something like the tiny gold beads created in Tell Yunatsite.
